WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hi everyone. As the gentleman said, I am Eric Leung, and I'm a data scientist at the Walt Disney Company working on marketing and content analytics.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:24.000
And last year, we started a project with ESPN, where they wanted to understand the effectiveness of their ads on live TV on the TV-watching households.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:33.000
More specifically, they were interested in how well these ads converted these households into cross-channel platforms.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:42.000
So, for example, subscribing to the Disney Plus Bundle or engaging with the ESPN website in some manner.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
When we started this process, we started with an R Script on one of our laptops.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:57.000
But by the end of it, we scaled up our operations, used Databricks for our workflows, and even threw in some Python in there.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:05.000
So today, I want to share three lessons that we learned in doing this process, and hopefully some of these resonate with you.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
The first one I want to share is don't reinvent the wheel.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
So for some background for us, we've done some marketing campaigns more in the email marketing space,

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:26.000
where we could separate groups into a holdout group and a testing group and send emails just to our test group.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Now we're thinking, oh, can we use the same methodology for viewership?

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
However, you can't really go into somebody's house and say, you watch some ads and you don't.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.000
So we had to find some other way to do this.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Luckily, some of our colleagues were working with Hulu on a marketing campaign,

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
and were making use of a counterfactual model to do this modeling.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.000
And even though they're different platforms, Hulu being streaming and our work was in the live TV space,

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:06.000
there's some commonalities that we could use to then refactor our code enough from theirs to our own project, hence not reinventing the wheel there.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
The next lesson I want to share is to use the best available tool for the job.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:22.000
So the ads that we started with were, say, watching MLB and running this, again, on our script on your own laptop.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:28.000
ESPN was also interested in how these ads would work on the other sports leagues that they have access to.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.000
And in my mind, I'm like, okay, now we have an R script running now five times on one laptop.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And this is how I kind of felt where we had this new model that we had to implement and refactor,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:45.000
but also scaling up our processes to handle all these other different sports leagues.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:52.000
So after going through some brainstorming, we're thinking, oh, okay, maybe we just need some sort of server to offload some of our compute,

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
maybe an Amazon web service or even Posit Connect.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Unfortunately, we didn't have access to those.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:04.000
But coincidentally, our group also recently got access to Databricks.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:10.000
And after talking to some colleagues, we realized it was the best available tool that we had,

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:18.000
where it could offload some compute, but also organize some of our data workflows in their workflows feature.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And the last lesson I'll leave you with is to budget time to make use of these new tools.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
And so before, we had just things on our laptop and adding in some Databricks, right?

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
So this will take some time, and we're committed to this.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And I was like, how long could this take?

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
Maybe a couple of weeks?

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:46.000
It turns out it took nearly two to three months to even just go through all the quirks and refactor our code,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
putting things, getting used to Databricks, and et cetera.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.000
So I would say, yeah, budget some time to make use of new tools or even existing tools.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.000
So in sum, my three lessons that I want to give you is don't reinvent the wheel if you don't have to.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
Maybe you have some open source project that you can look at.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Use not only the best tool for the job, but also the one that you have available to.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:14.000
And then lastly, to budget time into your project plan to get used to these new tools

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
and to deliver your project successfully.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.000
So thank you.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Thank you.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Thank you.

